7. occidione occisum: the figu- ra etymologica, i.e. the bringing together of two words from the same stem, which are closely con· nected logically and grammati· cally, was a favorite device in col- loquial Latin. cf. eg. from Plaut. Pseud: νἠιὶεινε miser, 13; iudo lu- dere, 243 cursim currere, 3 583 eou- dimeutis condire, 820. The same figure is common in the Letters, eg. solacio consolamur, Aet. 4. 6. 13 fiacile facies, Fam. 3. 9. 13 amavi amorem tuum, Ep. LXI. 13 utsuum gaudium gauderemus, Cael, Fam. 8. 2.1. See also coprus occidione occiderit, Pkil. 14. 36.—quo ... recessisse: the writer skilfully conveys the impression that the retreat of the Parthians was the result of his own action.
